Jade Airi (anime_zelda_lover_ ) 08-Mar-21 09:38 AM
Idk, like I want to draw. I have a wip currently that I just need to color. But, I’ve just been trying to think of ideas. Sadly none are coming to me. I’ve been mostly in the mindset of writing. But still would enjoy going back to art.

whitkit 08-Mar-21 09:40 AM
ive been doing this for days also oh my gosh. i have a bad habit of forcing myself to work on it but i think your body is telling you to take it easy
Link 08-Mar-21 09:41 AM
I’d say, just go with your own flow. It’s understandable to get bored with certain things in a certain amount of time. But, maybe if you draw or write your own story, you’ll most likely enjoy it. I usually write stories with me in different movies and other dimensions. It makes me feel calm, and gives the ambience that I end up desiring
Jade Airi (anime_zelda_lover_ ) 08-Mar-21 09:42 AM
Yeah, that’s what I’ve been doing. I’ll open up procreate. Make a new empty canvas then be like.. “alright here’s what I kinda want to draw.” Then I just, immediately close it. Normally getting inspiration for a certain media. Like realistic, black and white that I find from scrolling through insta. But then again half of my mind is like “that’s easy” while the rest is “it’ll take a long time for you to get that good”
Mickey 08-Mar-21 09:46 AM
If I can make an observation, and offer a piece of advice: the biggest enemy to inspiration is comparison. If you’re frequently in the mindset of “oh, it’ll take forever for me to be that good”, it’ll imbed in your mind and prevent you from wanting to progress. I recommend turning your mindset (and believe me, I struggle with this too) and instead saying “any practice I make is furthering my goals”. Some words written is better than none at all. A crappy (in your own opinion) piece of art is still practice you didn’t have before.
Better to accomplish something even if it’s not perfect than allow yourself to not even try.
Link 08-Mar-21 09:46 AM
Hey, you just keep on doing it. It may be difficult, but that won’t mean you won’t get better and better. Progression is key to your life, it’s the steps that you need to take to get to the next objective. And then once you reached the top, you’ll enjoy the reward, and that is the beauty and freshness of your accomplishment. (edited)
